      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-5 shadow-sm">
          <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer">What is a containerized centrifuge system?</summary>
          <p class="text-text-light mt-3 text-sm">A containerized centrifuge system is a complete, self-contained centrifuge module housed inside a standard ISO shipping container (20-foot or 40-foot). The container includes the centrifuge, pumps, heaters, controls, piping, and all auxiliaries needed for plug-and-play operation. These systems are used for remote oilfield, offshore platform, and mobile fluid processing applications where no permanent building or infrastructure exists.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-5 shadow-sm">
          <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer">What types of centrifuges can be containerized?</summary>
          <p class="text-text-light mt-3 text-sm">Both disc stack centrifuges (for light oils, diesel, lube oil) and decanter centrifuges (for heavy crude oil, sludge dewatering) can be containerized. A typical container may house a single centrifuge or a multi-stage system combining both types for sequential separation.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-5 shadow-sm">
          <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer">What are the main benefits of a containerized centrifuge?</summary>
          <p class="text-text-light mt-3 text-sm">Key benefits include: no building or permanent installation required; ISO-standard dimensions allow easy transport by truck, rail, or ship; plug-and-play startup at remote locations; explosion-proof (Class 1 Div 2) classification available; can process up to 2 barrels per minute of light crude oil; and can be returned or relocated after project completion.</p>
        </details>
        <details class="bg-white rounded-xl border border-gray-200 p-5 shadow-sm">
          <summary class="font-semibold text-navy cursor-pointer">What power supply does a containerized centrifuge require?</summary>
          <p class="text-text-light mt-3 text-sm">Containerized centrifuge systems typically require 480 VAC three-phase power, drawing up to 500 amps with electric preheaters included. Generator power is supported for fully off-grid remote operations. Specific power requirements depend on the centrifuge size and heating capacity.</p>
        </details>
